@page
@model TINWeb.Pages.Help.EstimationLogicModel
@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Estimation Logic";
}

<div class="container mt-4">
    <h1>Estimation Logic</h1>
    <p class="text-muted lead">How the Company Survey Estimation page calculates forecasted values for each metric.</p>

    <div class="alert alert-info">
        <strong>General principle:</strong> All calculations first check whether an actual recorded value exists for the target financial year. If one is found it is used directly. If not, the system falls back through a defined algorithm chain specific to each metric.
    </div>

    <nav class="mb-4">
        <ul class="list-unstyled d-flex flex-wrap gap-2">
            <li><a href="#revenue" class="btn btn-outline-secondary btn-sm">Total Revenue</a></li>
            <li><a href="#employment" class="btn btn-outline-secondary btn-sm">Employment</a></li>
            <li><a href="#wages" class="btn btn-outline-secondary btn-sm">Wages &amp; Salaries</a></li>
            <li><a href="#rd" class="btn btn-outline-secondary btn-sm">Research &amp; Development</a></li>
            <li><a href="#salesmarketing" class="btn btn-outline-secondary btn-sm">Sales &amp; Marketing</a></li>
            <li><a href="#ebitda" class="btn btn-outline-secondary btn-sm">EBITDA</a></li>
            <li><a href="#regions" class="btn btn-outline-secondary btn-sm">Regional Revenue (10 regions)</a></li>
        </ul>
    </nav>

    
    <div class="card mb-4" id="revenue">
        <div class="card-header fw-semibold">Total Revenue</div>
        <div class="card-body">
            <p class="mb-2">Uses the <strong>log-linear trend fit</strong> algorithm. Steps in priority order:</p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <strong>Actual value</strong> — if the company has a recorded Total Revenue answer for the target financial year, that value is returned immediately.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Log-linear trend (minimum 3 positive points)</strong> — takes up to the 5 most recent prior-year positive values and fits an OLS regression on <code>ln(value)</code> vs financial year:
                    <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 my-2 font-monospace small">
                        slope = Σ[(year − meanYear) × (ln(value) − meanLnValue)] / Σ[(year − meanYear)²]<br />
                        forecast = exp(meanLnValue + slope × (targetYear − meanYear))
                    </div>
                    Requires <strong>≥ 3</strong> positive historical points. Result is unclamped (can be negative in theory, though practical values will not be).
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Sector CAGR fallback (active)</strong> — when fewer than 3 positive historical points are available for the company, the system computes a CAGR (Compound Annual Growth Rate) from the last 5 years of total revenue across <em>all companies in the same secondary sector</em> and applies that sector-level growth rate to forecast revenue. The forecast is calculated as:
                    <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 my-2 font-monospace small">
                        latestRevenue = most recent positive revenue value<br />
                        sectorCAGR = (endYearSectorRevenue / beginYearSectorRevenue) ^ (1 / yearsSpan) − 1<br />
                        forecast = latestRevenue × (1 + sectorCAGR) ^ yearsToForecast
                    </div>
                    If no secondary sector is assigned to the company or insufficient sector-level history exists, returns <em>not available</em>.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>No result</strong> — if fewer than 3 positive points exist, sector CAGR cannot be calculated, or sector data is unavailable, returns <em>not available</em>.
                </li>
            </ol>
        </div>
    </div>

    
    <div class="card mb-4" id="employment">
        <div class="card-header fw-semibold">Total Employment</div>
        <div class="card-body">
            <p class=\"mb-2\">Uses the same <strong>log-linear trend fit</strong> algorithm as Total Revenue. Steps in priority order:</p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <strong>Actual value</strong> — if the company has a recorded Total Employment answer for the target financial year, that value is returned immediately. Historical data from both the current and legacy employment question titles are combined.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Log-linear trend (minimum 3 positive points)</strong> — takes up to the 5 most recent prior-year positive values and fits an OLS regression on <code>ln(value)</code> vs financial year:
                    <div class=\"bg-light border rounded p-3 my-2 font-monospace small\">
                        slope = Σ[(year − meanYear) × (ln(value) − meanLnValue)] / Σ[(year − meanYear)²]<br />
                        forecast = exp(meanLnValue + slope × (targetYear − meanYear))
                    </div>
                    Requires <strong>≥ 3</strong> positive historical points.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Sector CAGR fallback (active)</strong> — when fewer than 3 positive historical points are available for the company, the system computes a CAGR from the last 5 years of total employment across <em>all companies in the same secondary sector</em> and applies that sector-level growth rate to forecast employment. The forecast is calculated as:
                    <div class=\"bg-light border rounded p-3 my-2 font-monospace small\">
                        latestEmployment = most recent positive employment value<br />
                        sectorCAGR = (endYearSectorEmployment / beginYearSectorEmployment) ^ (1 / yearsSpan) − 1<br />
                        forecast = latestEmployment × (1 + sectorCAGR) ^ yearsToForecast
                    </div>
                    If no secondary sector is assigned to the company or insufficient sector-level history exists, returns <em>not available</em>.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>No result</strong> — if fewer than 3 positive points exist, sector CAGR cannot be calculated, or sector data is unavailable, returns <em>not available</em>.
                </li>
            </ol>
        </div>
    </div>

    
    <div class="card mb-4" id="wages">
        <div class="card-header fw-semibold">Wages &amp; Salaries</div>
        <div class="card-body">
                <p class="mb-2">Uses <strong>log-linear trend fit</strong> with a higher minimum and an active sector-ratio fallback. Ratios are calculated from the primary sector using the last 5 years of wages-to-revenue data.</p>
            <ol>
                <li><strong>Actual value</strong> for target year → returned directly.</li>
                <li>
                        <strong>Log-linear trend (&gt; 3 positive points)</strong> — same OLS on <code>ln(value)</code> as Total Revenue, but requires <strong>more than 3</strong> data points (i.e. ≥ 4).
                </li>
                <li>
                        <strong>Sector-ratio fallback (active)</strong> — when fewer than 4 positive historical points are available for the company, calculates the average ratio of <em>wages-to-revenue</em> from all companies in the same primary sector over the last 5 years and applies that ratio to the company's forecasted revenue:
                    <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 my-2 font-monospace small">
                            sectorRatio = (sum of sector wages) / (sum of sector revenue) over last 5 years<br />
                            forecast = forecastedRevenue × sectorRatio
                    </div>
                        If no primary sector is assigned or insufficient sector-level history exists, returns <em>not available</em>.
                </li>
                <li><strong>No result</strong> if neither condition is met.</li>
            </ol>
        </div>
    </div>

    
    <div class="card mb-4" id="rd">
        <div class="card-header fw-semibold">Research &amp; Development</div>
        <div class="card-body">
                <p class="mb-2">Uses the <strong>log-linear trend fit</strong> algorithm with an active sector-ratio fallback. Ratios are calculated from the primary sector using the last 5 years of R&D-to-revenue data.</p>
            <ol>
                <li><strong>Actual value</strong> for target year → returned directly.</li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Log-linear trend (≥ 3 positive points)</strong> — same OLS on <code>ln(value)</code> as Total Revenue across up to 5 prior years.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Sector-ratio fallback (active)</strong> — when fewer than 3 positive historical points are available for the company, calculates the average ratio of <em>R&D-to-revenue</em> from all companies in the same primary sector over the last 5 years and applies that ratio to the company's forecasted revenue:
                        <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 my-2 font-monospace small">
                            sectorRatio = (sum of sector R&D) / (sum of sector revenue) over last 5 years<br />
                            forecast = forecastedRevenue × sectorRatio
                        </div>
                        If no primary sector is assigned or insufficient sector-level history exists, returns <em>not available</em>.
                    </li>
                    <li><strong>No result</strong> if neither condition is met.</li>
            </ol>
        </div>
    </div>

    
    <div class="card mb-4" id="salesmarketing">
        <div class="card-header fw-semibold">Sales &amp; Marketing</div>
        <div class="card-body">
                <p class="mb-2">Uses the <strong>log-linear trend fit</strong> algorithm with an active sector-ratio fallback. Ratios are calculated from the primary sector using the last 5 years of S&M-to-revenue data.</p>
            <ol>
                <li><strong>Actual value</strong> for target year → returned directly.</li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Log-linear trend (≥ 3 positive points)</strong> — same OLS on <code>ln(value)</code> as Total Revenue across up to 5 prior years.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Sector-ratio fallback (active)</strong> — when fewer than 3 positive historical points are available for the company, calculates the average ratio of <em>S&M-to-revenue</em> from all companies in the same primary sector over the last 5 years and applies that ratio to the company's forecasted revenue:
                        <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 my-2 font-monospace small">
                            sectorRatio = (sum of sector S&M) / (sum of sector revenue) over last 5 years<br />
                            forecast = forecastedRevenue × sectorRatio
                        </div>
                        If no primary sector is assigned or insufficient sector-level history exists, returns <em>not available</em>.
                    </li>
                    <li><strong>No result</strong> if neither condition is met.</li>
            </ol>
        </div>
    </div>

    
    <div class="card mb-4" id="ebitda">
        <div class="card-header fw-semibold">EBITDA</div>
        <div class="card-body">
            <p class="mb-2">Uses <strong>linear regression</strong> (equivalent to Excel's <code>FORECAST.LINEAR</code>), not log-linear, because EBITDA can be negative.</p>
            <ol>
                <li><strong>Actual value</strong> for target year → returned directly.</li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Sector-ratio fallback</strong> (if ≤ 3 historical points and fallback is enabled — currently inactive):
                    <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 my-2 font-monospace small">
                        estimate = revenue × EbitdaPrimaryRatio + revenue × EbitdaSecondaryRatio
                    </div>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Linear regression (≥ 4 historical points)</strong> — OLS on raw values vs financial year across all prior-year non-null points:
                    <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 my-2 font-monospace small">
                        slope = Σ[(year − avgYear) × (value − avgValue)] / Σ[(year − avgYear)²]<br />
                        intercept = avgValue − slope × avgYear<br />
                        forecast = slope × targetYear + intercept<br />
                        <span class="text-muted">// floored at 0</span>
                    </div>
                    The result is floored at <code>0</code> (negative EBITDA estimates are zeroed).
                </li>
                <li><strong>No result</strong> if fewer than 4 points and fallback is inactive.</li>
            </ol>
        </div>
    </div>

    
    <div class="card mb-4" id="regions">
        <div class="card-header fw-semibold">Regional Revenue (NZ, Australia, China, Rest of Asia, North America, Europe, Middle East, Latin America, Africa, Other)</div>
        <div class="card-body">
            <p class="mb-2">All 10 regional revenue metrics share the <strong>same log-linear growth fit algorithm</strong> with a <em>lower</em> minimum threshold than the total revenue metric, plus an optional sector export-ratio fallback.</p>
            <ol>
                <li><strong>Actual value</strong> for the target year → returned directly.</li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Log-linear growth fit (minimum 2 positive points)</strong> — takes up to the 5 most recent prior-year positive values:
                    <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 my-2 font-monospace small">
                        slope = Σ[(year − meanYear) × (ln(value) − meanLnValue)] / Σ[(year − meanYear)²]<br />
                        forecast = exp(meanLnValue + slope × (targetYear − meanYear))<br />
                        <span class="text-muted">// floored at 0</span>
                    </div>
                    Requires <strong>≥ 2</strong> positive historical points. Result is floored at <code>0</code>.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Sector export-ratio fallback (currently inactive for all regions)</strong> — if enabled, applies a per-region export ratio constant to the current year's total company revenue:
                    <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 my-2 font-monospace small">
                        estimate = totalRevenue × RegionExportRatio
                    </div>
                    This is configured in code (<code>EnableRevenueXxxSectorFallback = false</code>) but not active for any region at this time — data is not yet available to calibrate the ratios.
                </li>
                <li><strong>No result</strong> if fewer than 2 positive prior-year points and the fallback is inactive.</li>
            </ol>
            <h6 class="mt-3">Difference vs Total Revenue log-linear</h6>
            <table class="table table-sm table-bordered">
                <thead class="table-light">
                    <tr><th>Property</th><th>Total Revenue / R&amp;D / Sales &amp; Marketing / Employment</th><th>Regional Revenue (all 10)</th></tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                    <tr><td>Minimum positive points</td><td>3</td><td>2</td></tr>
                    <tr><td>Floor at 0</td><td>No</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
                    <tr><td>Sector fallback</td><td>No</td><td>Yes (inactive)</td></tr>
                </tbody>
            </table>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="mb-4">
        <a asp-page="/Index" class="btn btn-secondary">Back to Home</a>
    </div>
</div>

